abid.title: AbID for MARC should cache the holding record and display the full 852 in the report.

comments.body: Instead of the permanent call number for the report (for former call number), including the entire 852 field as a string would provide the full information (including if there was a subfield x, or a different field indicator, etc.). Is it possible to grab that from the holding instead of the permanent call number?

Trey's idea about adding a prefix for ReCAP is fantastic.  Totally fits our cataloging situation as well as Alma process planning in CaMS.
If this simple addition of another value to the list is considered to be development work requiring review, please tell me how to make a ticket for it.  Also, please tell me what factors are considered in such review, and to whom I should make the case.

I can add both of those as tickets, but I don't want to block this PR over them. The holding thing is possible, but it means an earlier call to fetch the holding vs the item, so I just grabbed the immediately available call number for now.

I agree that my request for the entire 852 should not block this PR. I just thought if it was a simple fix, it could be implemented. I hadn't thought about what information the item API call returned.

OK with me.  I think we can live with permanent call number only in the report.  No reason to delay release.
This thing is just fantastic.  It will be fantastic+ with a ReCAP prefix.  The data entry form redesign was vital.  I was terrified that we'd be stuck with the original version, which was dysfunctional.  Hence the text file idea.  I am so glad to leave all that behind.  This really is a dream come true.  It will have deep meaning for Special Collections.  Where do I go to sing the praises publicly?

Here's something unexpected.  I entered 3 barcodes linked to the same holdings record 22750856150006421.  An AbID was created for each barcode.  The last one,  F-000191, became the call number.  The "dream" included a check for holdings records IDs prior to generating AbIDs, with only one AbID only being created for each distinct holding.  In this case I would have expected only F-000189 to exist.  That's how the old one worked by checking Voyager MFHD IDs during the scanning process.
It's not a dreadful problem but might lead to someone looking around for "missing" numbers in the sequence.
Another ticket, or fix before releasing?

> It's not a dreadful problem but might lead to someone looking around for "missing" numbers in the sequence.
> Another ticket, or fix before releasing?

If you can use the system without this being in place I'd prefer a ticket. It's a little complicated because I'm assuming that if this happens I just shouldn't create an AbID for the second two barcodes? And does this only apply if I scan these things in together, or in general if an AbID already exists should I not overwrite it - even though Mike shared a use case for sometimes overwriting the AbID. Is it just that if an AbID exists already for the same holding don't mint a new one?

In any case, a ticket would be good unless this renders the system unusable. Thanks!
Does having the previous permanent call number help with this?

> Where do I go to sing the praises publicly?

You just did. :heart: You're the best. This is really appreciated, thank you. In general github ticket comments, contacting our supervisors, or the #gratitude channel are a good way to do this.

We can use it, so no delay on our behalf.  I may tell Mike to hold of on multi-volume sets for a while.
But I'm referring to a basic structural feature of MARC.   In Voyager we did this MFHD ID check live during barcode scan.  Good ole Macro Express could get it from the item record header.  I was thinking that for Alma you'd take the barcodes we provide, check for holdings, and then use the holdings list rather than barcodes to make the call numbers since call numbers pertain to holdings, not items.  That's what the "dream" document says.
I don't think permanent call number relates.  That's kind of a marginal concern, just to keep up with historical practice that probably doesn't have customers any more!

comments.body:
Sorry, we may have confused the discussion of DataSpace and ORCiD integration. This isn't for having ORCiD  as a sign-on option on DataSpace, but more specifically with the ORCiD SSO login option, which is available at: https://orcid.org/institutional-signin

Princeton University does show up in the list to use NetID for ORCiD login.

Not sure if there's an appropriate GitHub repo for this.

dspace-development.title: Users expect that DataSpace Tasks can be assigned to other users

comments.body: The intent of this is because multiple PPPL and Princeton reviewers/approvers are notified via email. Because many of the reviewers are department heads and are not fully familiar with the process, they aren't sure if this is a task for them or not. This often leaves deposits in a limbo state with no one reviewing it.
